# DOM Day 1 - Introduction to DOM

## Topics Learned

* DOM (Document Object Model)
* HTML `id` attribute
* `document.getElementById()`
* `innerText`
* Button click events using `onclick`
* Changing webpage content with JavaScript

---

## What is DOM?

DOM (Document Object Model) is a representation of an HTML page that JavaScript can access and modify.

JavaScript uses the DOM to:

* Change text
* Change styles
* Handle button clicks
* Update webpage content dynamically

---

## HTML Example

```html
<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>

<button onclick="changeText()">
    Click Me
</button>

<button onclick="reset()">
    Reset
</button>
```

---

## JavaScript Example

```javascript
function changeText() {
    document.getElementById("title").innerText =
        "Atharv Narendra Thakare";
}

function reset() {
    document.getElementById("title").innerText =
        "Hello";
}
```

---

## Important Concepts

### id

```html
<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
```

The `id` gives an HTML element a unique name so JavaScript can find it.

---

### getElementById()

```javascript
document.getElementById("title")
```

Finds the HTML element whose id is `"title"`.

---

### innerText

```javascript
document.getElementById("title").innerText = "Atharv";
```

Changes the text inside the selected element.

---

## Before and After

### Before

```html
<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
```

### After

```javascript
document.getElementById("title").innerText = "Atharv";
```

Result:

```html
<h1 id="title">Atharv</h1>
```

---

## Key Takeaways

* DOM allows JavaScript to control HTML pages.
* `id` uniquely identifies an element.
* `getElementById()` finds an element.
* `innerText` reads or changes text.
* `onclick` runs a function when a button is clicked.

